Why are there regional banks? We have   talked a   lot recently about the c=
entral fragility of the business model: Banks take short-term deposits to f=
und long-term loans, and when interest rates go up their depositors might l=
eave (or demand higher interest) as their loans lose value, making them fai=
l. Giant global banks mitigate this problem by being =E2=80=9Ctoo big to fa=
il,=E2=80=9D which means not only that if their depositors flee the governm=
ent will bail them out, but also that their creditors might reasonably thin=
k something like =E2=80=9Cwell, if JPMorgan fails, then the world has proba=
bly ended, so I=E2=80=99m not going to worry too much about their credit ri=
sk.=E2=80=9D
  [1]
=C2=A0But regional banks don=E2=80=99t really have that advantage
  [2]
: They=C2=A0are=C2=A0fragile, and their depositors notice their fragility, =
and they can go bust rather easily, as they have found out this year.
When this happens, there=C2=A0is more concentration of US banking at the to=
o-big-to-fail banks, either because JPMorgan Chase & Co.   buys failed regi=
onal banks, or because people  just take their money out of rickety regiona=
l banks and   put it at safer big banks.
  [3]
=C2=A0Some people think this is bad: Concentration is bad, too-big-to-failn=
ess is bad. Other people are not so sure. What, they ask, are regional bank=
s=C2=A0for? Why does the US have so very many banks, so many of which are s=
mall and under-supervised and liable to vanish over a weekend and cause a l=
ot of trouble as they go? Why shouldn=E2=80=99t everyone bank at a few big =
banks that are closely monitored, and robustly supported, by the government=
?
The intuitive answer is that regional banks are=C2=A0regional, they are loc=
al, they have relationships and expertise specific to some part of the coun=
try. Historically this answer was often about deposits: You=E2=80=99d open =
an account at the bank in your town, because you had to go to the bank to g=
et your money, and it was easiest to go to the bank in your town. But now p=
eople bank online and get their money from national ATM networks, and the b=
ig banks probably have better banking apps than the small ones. There is le=
ss reason to prefer having a checking account at your local bank.
  [4]

But the local expertise advantage is real in=C2=A0banks=E2=80=99 lending=C2=
=A0business: If you want to buy a house, a bank that knows your neighborhoo=
d will be better equipped to underwrite your mortgage. If you have a small =
business and want to=C2=A0borrow money to expand, a local banker might have=
 a better sense of your prospects than a big bank, and might be more flexib=
le and willing to work with you. And in fact smaller banks are important pl=
ayers in=C2=A0commercial real estate and    small-business lending, where l=
ocal knowledge is more important.
Still it is odd to think of regional banks as, like, good credit-underwriti=
ng and customer-service businesses stapled to a wildly risky funding model.=
 Why have the wildly risky funding model? We have also   talked a   lot   r=
ecently about the idea of =E2=80=9Cnarrow banking,=E2=80=9D in which:
=09Deposits would=C2=A0just be kept at the Federal Reserve, they would just=
 be=C2=A0money, they would=C2=A0not be funding for banks to make loans; and=
=09Loans would be funded by locked-up, long-term investors with the appropr=
iate time horizons. Some lending fund would raise money from investors who =
commit their money for 10 years, and then it would go out and make 10-year =
loans, and it would never have to worry about the investors asking for thei=
r money back before the loans matured.

This would be=C2=A0safer=C2=A0than the current system of fractional reserve=
 banking; it would get rid of the central fragility of banking. Something w=
ould probably be lost: Fractional-reserve banking is   a way to get society=
 to take more risk, to transform risky investments into safe deposits. (=E2=
=80=9CFinancial systems help us overcome a collective action problem,=E2=80=
=9D  writes Steve Randy Waldman: =E2=80=9CIn a world of investment projects=
 whose costs and risks are perfectly transparent, most individuals would be=
 frightened.=E2=80=9D) But some version of it is happening, a little bit, a=
nyway: Deposits are flowing   into money market funds that just park them a=
t the Fed, and=C2=A0private credit funds are becoming increasingly importan=
t in lending.
If you like narrow banking, you will want to have=C2=A0answers to some prac=
tical questions like =E2=80=9Cwho decides who gets the loans=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Care these loan funds going to hire a bunch of lending officers in =
every small town to make small-business loans?=E2=80=9D But you can sort of=
 imagine it with a reshuffling of the pieces of the current system. What if=
 regional banks kept=C2=A0making loans, the thing they are good at, but ins=
tead of=C2=A0taking deposits=C2=A0they went out and got funding=C2=A0from t=
he long-term, locked-up, run-proof=C2=A0loan funds? What if you kept the cr=
edit-underwriting and customer-service functions of regional banking, but g=
ot rid of the wildly risky funding model?
Well I=E2=80=99m sure there would be all sorts of costs and disruptions =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0banks like the risky funding model because deposits are usually=
 pretty=C2=A0cheap=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0but  here=E2=80=99s a gesture in tha=
t direction:

Blackstone is in discussions with large US regional banks about providing t=
hem with extra firepower to lend to companies amid signs the recent industr=
y turmoil is morphing into a credit crunch.
Jon Gray, president of Blackstone, told the Financial Times his company was=
 talking to regional banks about entering into partnerships, which would in=
volve lenders making or =E2=80=9Coriginating=E2=80=9D loans that the privat=
e equity group can funnel to its insurance customers.

That is from Antoine Gara at the Financial Times; it goes on:

Gray said regional banks were still best placed to decide whether to lend t=
o commercial and real estate clients, describing them as having =E2=80=9Cpo=
werful origination capabilities and relationships=E2=80=9D.
But he said groups such as his could be a =E2=80=9Cvaluable partner=E2=80=
=9D by helping to offload some of the risk after a loan has been securitise=
d. =E2=80=9CRather than putting all [of the risk] on its balance sheet, may=
be they keep 50 cents [on the dollar], and put 50 cents with us.=E2=80=9D
Blackstone plans to channel the securities to asset-hungry insurers which w=
ould hold the debt to maturity. =E2=80=9CWhat=E2=80=99s really changed from=
 our standpoint is that we have a very low-cost capital because of our insu=
rance clients,=E2=80=9D Gray said.
Blackstone does not have a controlling stake in any insurers but offers ass=
et management services to large players such as AIG. These customers, Gray =
said, are a natural home for assets that might otherwise be held on banks=
=E2=80=99 balance sheets.

Insurance companies have long-term liabilities (life insurance, annuities, =
etc.) that they use to fund long-term assets. They are natural long-term bu=
yers of long-term loans. They do not necessarily have branches=C2=A0in lots=
 of places to=C2=A0make those loans. Regional banks, meanwhile, do have bra=
nches=C2=A0that are good at making those loans, but they do not have partic=
ularly long-term funding to own them for the long term. These days, as thei=
r deposits leave, some of them don=E2=80=99t have much funding at all. Ther=
e are trades to be done.

