In the olden days, simplistically, there were two sorts of shareholders of =
public companies. There were=C2=A0active shareholders, owner-operators, sto=
ck promoters, robber barons, railroad tycoons, etc., who would buy 100% or =
51% or 15% of some company and involve themselves in=C2=A0running=C2=A0it, =
going to board meetings and making strategic decisions. And there were=C2=
=A0passive=C2=A0shareholders, regular investors, who would buy 100 shares o=
f some company to get dividends.
Over time, as the stock market grew, these archetypal shareholders were inc=
reasingly pools of capital rather than individual humans. (None of this his=
tory is particularly=C2=A0real, by the way; it is just schematic.) Active s=
hareholders are now often private equity firms, corporate raiders,=C2=A0act=
ivist hedge funds, etc., who=C2=A0buy 100% or 51% or 15% of some company an=
d try to change its management. Passive shareholders are often mutual funds=
 or other asset managers, who pool capital from regular investors and buy 0=
.1% or 1% or 9% of some company for investment purposes.
There are, in US law, lots of=C2=A0rules=C2=A0about corporate ownership, ab=
out who can own a company and who has to approve any change in ownership.=
=C2=A0Some of these rules apply to every company, or every public company: =
 Securities law regulates how people can take over companies, what they hav=
e to disclose, how they have to treat other shareholders, etc.;  antitrust =
law regulates how people can acquire multiple companies in the same industr=
y, to prevent anyone from gaining monopoly power. Others are industry-speci=
fic: Lots of industries have their own regulators, who will want to vet the=
 owners of the companies they regulate, so if you want to acquire a  bank o=
r a  casino or a   defense contractor or a  television network, you will ha=
ve to get the approval of the relevant industry regulator.
Often =E2=80=94=C2=A0not always, but often =E2=80=94=C2=A0these rules will =
make a distinction between active and passive owners: Active owner-operator=
s often need to get these approvals, while passive investor-shareholders of=
ten do not, or can get them quickly and automatically. If you want to buy 5=
1% of a publicly traded=C2=A0casino company and run it, that implicates sec=
urities law and antitrust law and casino regulation. If you want to buy 100=
 shares of a casino company in your 401(k), that does=C2=A0not. There is so=
metimes a size-based distinction=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0acquiring more than $X=
 or Y% of the shares triggers review =E2=80=94=C2=A0but often there is also=
 a subjective intent distinction, where even if you acquire more than $X or=
 Y%, as long as you are a passive investor, that=E2=80=99s fine.
The problem is that, in modern markets, the passive investors have become m=
ore active.
  [5]
=C2=A0Modern asset managers feel some fiduciary duty to their investors, no=
t just to pick good stocks, but also to do =E2=80=9Cstewardship,=E2=80=9D t=
o supervise the managers of the companies whose stocks they own and tell th=
em how to run their businesses better. (In fact many modern asset managers =
don=E2=80=99t pick stocks at all; they just buy the stocks in the index, wh=
ich makes stewardship more important.)
Not all of this is about environmental, social and governance issues, but a=
 lot of it is, in part because ESG has recently been a good marketing pitch=
 for many asset managers and in part because, if you=E2=80=99re a very dive=
rsified investor, you may not have any great ideas for how any particular c=
ompany can improve its margins, but good governance and climate change affe=
ct=C2=A0all=C2=A0of your investments so you=E2=80=99ll have some more devel=
oped views. But the point here isn=E2=80=99t really about ESG; it=E2=80=99s=
 about the fact that asset managers are fiduciaries for their investors, an=
d =E2=80=9Cehh we just let companies do what they want and don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0bother checking up on them=E2=80=9D feels lazy and unprofessional. (Wher=
eas, if you own 100 shares of some company in your personal account, it wou=
ld be sort of crazy for=C2=A0you=C2=A0to try to check up on management.)=C2=
=A0
What does this mean for all the rules about ownership?=C2=A0I think it crea=
tes hard problems: The rules were written when the distinction between acti=
ve owner-operators and passive investors was a bit sharper, and they don=E2=
=80=99t give very clear answers now. The antitrust rules distinguish passiv=
e owners who acquire stock =E2=80=9Csolely for the purpose of investment=E2=
=80=9D from active owners who try to =E2=80=9Cinfluence the business decisi=
ons=E2=80=9D of the company, but surely an index fund with 5% of a company=
=E2=80=99s stock is=C2=A0mostly=C2=A0the former but also a little bit the l=
atter. SEC rules distinguish passive owners who buy stock =E2=80=9Cin the o=
rdinary course of [their] business and not with the purpose nor with the ef=
fect of changing or influencing the control of the issuer=E2=80=9D from act=
ive owners who try to =E2=80=9Cchange or influence the control=E2=80=9D of =
the company; surely an index fund with 5% of a company=E2=80=99s stock boug=
ht it =E2=80=9Cin the ordinary course of its business=E2=80=9D and without =
planning to change the control of the company, but can its stewardship team=
 come in and talk about governance, or is that =E2=80=9Cinfluencing the con=
trol=E2=80=9D?
So a certain amount of action in securities regulation has to do with polic=
ing this now somewhat blurry line between active and passive shareholders. =
(Ask=C2=A0  Elon Musk!) A significant=C2=A0amount of   action in=C2=A0antit=
rust enforcement, and a   huge amount of   action in antitrust scholarship,=
 has to do with this shifting line: Historically it would have been somewha=
t insane to say =E2=80=9Can index fund is an antitrust problem because it o=
wns stocks of lots of competing companies,=E2=80=9D but as asset managers h=
ave become more interested in stewardship, that has become a far more popul=
ar thing to say,   even among antitrust regulators.
You see less of this action in industry-specific regulatory regimes, but I =
guess that could=C2=A0change. In particular, if you don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0like=
=C2=A0asset-manager stewardship, these industry regulatory regimes might be=
 a promising way to check the power of asset managers, or at least to annoy=
 them. And =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t like asset-manager stewardship=E2=
=80=9D means mostly =E2=80=9Cif you don=E2=80=99t like ESG.=E2=80=9D
  [6]
=C2=A0So   here=E2=80=99s this:

