      Plugging oil wells
   =20
 =20

I  mentioned this in a footnote the other day, but perhaps it deserves more=
 attention. We were talking about oil companies doing stock buybacks. My ma=
in point was that if you are an oil-company executive, and you think that t=
he=C2=A0very long-term=C2=A0future of oil is bad (people will stop using it=
 for environmental reasons, etc.), but you have a lot of cash flow from oil=
 now (people use a lot of oil now), then you might consider returning that =
cash flow to shareholders, in the form of stock buybacks and dividends, rat=
her than investing it in your business for the long term. Because, by hypot=
hesis, your business does not have a long term.
There are counterarguments, with the main one being something like =E2=80=
=9Cpeople will always use energy, even if they don=E2=80=99t always use oil=
, and=C2=A0as an oil company, you are best positioned to=C2=A0develop=C2=A0=
the energy sources of the future, so you should invest your current oil cas=
h flows in long-term green energy projects.=E2=80=9D I think that is a reas=
onable argument, and I certainly don=E2=80=99t presume to know which choice=
 oil-company chief executive officers should make. I just wanted to point o=
ut that both choices make a certain sense, and that if you (1) don=E2=80=99=
t like stock buybacks but (2) do like environmental investing, you might fi=
nd oil-company buybacks a little bit more sympathetic.
But  in a footnote I added one particular reason to prefer stock buybacks o=
ver long-term investment:
In my schematic description, the value of oil drilling declines to zero in =
Year X. Lower numbers are possible! You could imagine a future where, in X =
years, (1) nobody uses oil and (2) everybody is going around suing oil comp=
anies for the costs of repairing environmental damage. In that scenario, be=
ing capital-light is a benefit: If you've given the money back to the share=
holders, they get to keep it, while if you've held onto it, it can go to pa=
y liabilities. The=C2=A0US coal industry=C2=A0has already very much discove=
red this point.
That is: When you=E2=80=99re done with an oil well, you have to clean it up=
 so it doesn=E2=80=99t just leak pollution forever. That is the responsibil=
ity of the company that drilled the well, and there are various rules and b=
onding mechanisms to try to make sure that an oil company that drilled a we=
ll sticks around to pay for cleaning it up. Those rules are imperfect. Gene=
rally speaking, if you=E2=80=99re a half-trillion-dollar global energy comp=
any, and you=E2=80=99ve got some wells that you=E2=80=99re done with, the g=
overnment is going to make you clean them up. If you=E2=80=99re a rotten hu=
sk of a former energy company with $26 in the bank, though, there=E2=80=99s=
 only so much the government can do. (It can take your $26.) If you are an =
oil company now, and things are good, and you return a dollar to shareholde=
rs, the shareholders keep the dollar. (It is pretty hard for the government=
 to claw back money distributed to public shareholders.) If you keep that d=
ollar to invest, the government might end up taking it to pay for cleaning =
up your wells. That dollar might be worth a lot more in shareholders=E2=80=
=99 hands than in yours.
I mean, if you are a shareholder-value-maximizing oil-company CEO, this is =
a reasonable calculation. If you are someone who doesn=E2=80=99t like stock=
 buybacks but likes environmental investing, you will=C2=A0not=C2=A0like th=
is; this is, schematically, a way for oil companies to get away with pollut=
ion without paying for it.
Anyway here=E2=80=99s  a New York Times story about plugging offshore oil w=
ells:

Ever since the first offshore platforms went up off Louisiana 85 years ago,=
 the Gulf of Mexico has been an oil and gas juggernaut. But decades of dril=
ling has left behind more than 14,000 old, unplugged wells at risk of sprin=
