<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run a business, you will always feel pr=
essure to tell some people that it=E2=80=99s going well and other people th=
at it=E2=80=99s going poorly. You will always want to tell=C2=A0<em>investo=
rs=C2=A0</em>that the business is going well, because then they will reward=
 you by giving you more capital. You will generally want to tell the=C2=A0<=
em>tax collectors=C2=A0</em>that the business is going poorly, because then=
 they will collect less money in taxes. (Thus, tax accounting and financial=
 accounting are sometimes different, and people sometimes=C2=A0get mad abou=
t it.) Other categories are more ambiguous: You might want to tell supplier=
s that business is going well (so they are comfortable increasing the relat=
ionship and selling you more stuff on credit), or that it is going poorly (=
so that they feel sorry for you and give you a discount). You might want to=
 tell employees that business is going well (so they don=E2=80=99t quit for=
 a more stable job), or that it is going poorly (so they don=E2=80=99t dema=
nd a raise).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ideally you would not <em>lie</em> to any of t=
hem, but there is a range of ways to characterize your business, and to mak=
e conditional predictions about an uncertain future. And everything is on t=
he internet these days, so it is often possible for one audience to find wh=
at you are telling another audience and say =E2=80=9Chey, you are telling u=
s two different things.=E2=80=9D And if you are a public company and one of=
 the audiences is your shareholders, someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0not necessarily=
 the shareholders! =E2=80=94=C2=A0might say =E2=80=9Chey, is this securitie=
s fraud?=E2=80=9D Because <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.co=
m/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGl=
jbGVzLzIwMjEtMDItMDMvZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1nb2VzLXRvLXN1cHJlbWUtY291cnQtaGVkZ2=
UtZnVuZHMtd29uLW9uLWdhbWVzdG9wLWtrcG9lNndzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MTEyM19NT05FWVNUV=
UZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUx=
MSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB25d7d4b4" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;">  everything is securities fraud</a>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A few years ago, the US Department of Labor pr=
oposed some new rules for investment advisers, and some companies that woul=
d be subject to the rules wrote comment letters to the DOL about how bad th=
e rules would be for their business, because =E2=80=9Cthis is a catastrophe=
 for investment advice=E2=80=9D is a good argument against the rules. But t=
hey also did investor calls where they told investors that the rules would =
be fine for their business, because =E2=80=9Cthis is a catastrophe for inve=
stment advice=E2=80=9D is a bad thing to tell your shareholders. And then S=
enator Elizabeth Warren =E2=80=94=C2=A0who supported the rule and didn=E2=
=80=99t like the investment industry =E2=80=94=C2=A0just wrote down all the=
 things they told the DOL, and all the things they told their investors, an=
d put them in a letter to the US Securities and Exchange Commission asking =
=E2=80=9Chey is this securities fraud or what?=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2Fyc=
mVuLnNlbmF0ZS5nb3YvZmlsZXMvZG9jdW1lbnRzLzIwMTYtMy0zMV9TZW5XYXJyZW5fTHRyX3Rv=
X1NFQy5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB81eb8b3d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> She wrote</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Both sets of industry claims - tha=
t the proposed rule will harm them and their business model, and that the p=
roposed rule will not harm them and their business model - cannot possibly =
be true. And if one these public statements is materially false, it would a=
ppear to violate long-standing interpretations of our securities laws.</p><=
/blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTYtMDMtMzEvc2VuYXRvci1kb2Vzbi10LWxpa2UtY29tcGFuaWVzLWx5aW5n=
LXRvLWdvdmVybm1lbnQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUxMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWF=
pbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb2=
5leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2e97f319" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked about it at =
the time</a>. It was a very fun rhetorical move.<a class=3D"footnote-index"=
 href=3D"#footnote-9" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display:=
 inline-block;">
<span>[9]</span>
</a>=C2=A0<em>Was=C2=A0</em>it fraud? I wrote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, the comments to the regula=
tors and the comments to the shareholders are both contingent predictions a=
bout the unknowable future, so you can't really hold anyone responsible if =
they turn out to be wrong. And nobody actually makes different unconditiona=
l quantified falsifiable predictions to the two different audiences -- no o=
ne says to the regulators "this rule will definitely cost us $100 million a=
 year no matter what we do in response," while also telling the shareholder=
s "this rule won't affect our bottom line at all no matter what." They make=
 vague, conditional predictions; they stress the problems to the regulators=
 and the solutions to the shareholders.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, awkward.=C2=A0Anyway here is a <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9wb2RjYXN0cy90aGUtam91cm5hbC9vbmUtaG9sbHl3b29kLXdyaXRlci1v=
bi10aGUtaW5kdXN0cnlzLWRpcmUtc2l0dWF0aW9uLzVlMWYxMDgyLTU4N2MtNDY5MS1iMTZjLTc=
3ZDVhMWE3NzRhNQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBeeb9e9f6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Jou=
rnal podcast</a> with television writer Michael Schur about the Hollywood w=
riters=E2=80=99 strike<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; =
background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Ryan Knutson:</strong> A lot of studio=
s say this is a bad time to be making major changes to writers pay. Most st=
reaming services are losing money, and many studios are under pressure from=
 Wall Street to cut costs. Warner Brothers, Discovery, and Paramount have a=
ll canceled projects lately, and companies like Disney have been laying peo=
ple off. How do you respond to that?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Michael Schur:</strong> It's very funn=
y, they say one thing on their investor calls and then a very different thi=
ng to us when we're in the negotiating room. On their investor calls, it's =
all rosy. We're going to make so much money. We're going to be profitable v=
ery soon. We're going to make X billions of dollars over the next Y years. =
And then when they get in a room with us, they're like, "Guys, you've picke=
d a really bad time to ask for a raise." We are like, we read the notes of =
your call. We know how much money you're projecting.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right when you are negotiating a union con=
tract you turn your pockets inside out and say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re broke=
, you gotta take a pay cut,=E2=80=9D and then when you have an investor day=
 you pull sacks of gold out of your pockets and say =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99re =
so rich it=E2=80=99s great.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s just that the union can h=
ear you, and the shareholders are litigious.</p>
