<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusine=
ss.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2=
FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDgvb2lsLWNvbXBhbmllcy1naXZlLWJhY2stdGhlLWNhc2g_Y21wa=
WQ9QkJEMDUxMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3Ns=
ZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cCede39982" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> mentioned this</a> in a footnote the other d=
ay, but perhaps it deserves more attention. We were talking about oil compa=
nies doing stock buybacks. My main point was that if you are an oil-company=
 executive, and you think that the=C2=A0<em>very long-term=C2=A0</em>future=
 of oil is bad (people will stop using it for environmental reasons, etc.),=
 but you have a lot of cash flow from oil now (people use a lot of oil now)=
, then you might consider returning that cash flow to shareholders, in the =
form of stock buybacks and dividends, rather than investing it in your busi=
ness for the long term. Because, by hypothesis, your business does not have=
 a long term.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are counterarguments, with the main one =
being something like =E2=80=9Cpeople will always use <em>energy</em>, even =
if they don=E2=80=99t always use <em>oil</em>, and=C2=A0as an oil company, =
you are best positioned to=C2=A0<em>develop=C2=A0</em>the energy sources of=
 the future, so you should invest your current oil cash flows in long-term =
green energy projects.=E2=80=9D I think that is a reasonable argument, and =
I certainly don=E2=80=99t presume to know which choice oil-company chief ex=
ecutive officers should make. I just wanted to point out that both choices =
make a certain sense, and that if you (1) don=E2=80=99t like stock buybacks=
 but (2) do like environmental investing, you might find oil-company buybac=
ks a little bit more sympathetic.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9u=
L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDgvb2lsLWNvbXBhbmllcy1naXZlLWJhY2stdGhlLWNhc2g_Y21=
waWQ9QkJEMDUxMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3=
NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZmI2Zvb3Rub3RlL=
TM/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBac45e0bf" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> in a footnote</a> I added on=
e particular reason to prefer stock buybacks over long-term investment:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In my schematic description, the v=
alue of oil drilling declines to zero in Year X. Lower numbers are possible=
! You could imagine a future where, in X years, (1) nobody uses oil and (2)=
 everybody is going around suing oil companies for the costs of repairing e=
nvironmental damage. In that scenario, being capital-light is a benefit: If=
 you've given the money back to the shareholders, they get to keep it, whil=
e if you've held onto it, it can go to pay liabilities. The=C2=A0<a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93=
d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy9kaXZlcnNpZmllZC1lbmVyZ3ktbmF0dXJhbC1nYXM=
td2VsbHMtbWV0aGFuZS1sZWFrcy0yMDIxLz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTExMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG=
1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MTEmdXRtX=
2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB90911c04" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">US coal industry</a>=C2=A0has already very much disc=
overed this point.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is: When you=E2=80=99re done with an oil =
well, you have to clean it up so it doesn=E2=80=99t just leak pollution for=
ever. That is the responsibility of the company that drilled the well, and =
there are various rules and bonding mechanisms to try to make sure that an =
oil company that drilled a well sticks around to pay for cleaning it up. Th=
ose rules are imperfect. Generally speaking, if you=E2=80=99re a half-trill=
ion-dollar global energy company, and you=E2=80=99ve got some wells that yo=
u=E2=80=99re done with, the government is going to make you clean them up. =
If you=E2=80=99re a rotten husk of a former energy company with $26 in the =
bank, though, there=E2=80=99s only so much the government can do. (It can t=
ake your $26.) If you are an oil company now, and things are good, and you =
return a dollar to shareholders, the shareholders keep the dollar. (It is p=
retty hard for the government to claw back money distributed to public shar=
eholders.) If you keep that dollar to invest, the government might end up t=
aking it to pay for cleaning up your wells. That dollar might be worth a lo=
t more in shareholders=E2=80=99 hands than in yours.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, if you are a shareholder-value-maximiz=
ing oil-company CEO, this is a reasonable calculation. If you are someone w=
ho doesn=E2=80=99t like stock buybacks but likes environmental investing, y=
ou will=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>like this; this is, schematically, a way for=
 oil companies to get away with pollution without paying for it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31452208.261438/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy=
5jb20vMjAyMy8wNS8wOC9jbGltYXRlL2d1bGYtb2YtbWV4aWNvLW9pbC13ZWxscy1wbHVnLmh0b=
Ww_dW5sb2NrZWRfYXJ0aWNsZV9jb2RlPXp5NElCN0J5azNSLXVGRnhQVjY1aE10VDUzb1YxSGlj=
dWhpdHRDQ0lvYVdTQUZBT1ZlM0prRkR5ZVN3OVEzOFVxNlg2V3ZPektyQTVKOWRWcHRhWk9PT3J=
NbHpsTW9PWDRKbHk3Mm9RNjJMQmhGVXhwdWRDdTJrMXl3ZXdaSWQ1ODhIdUtXWmJaTzBoYkxac2=
ZlWmI4QnJRVVE1SDh1TXNPQm5CUkJWMWpyMUF0ZzdYLXdtTVl1NTVFZWpUWnE4SUdEbEJnWGVzU=
jBrNW4yRGdrWVBTb2VzdjJhLW50cGNaRF82ZGk4S0ZEeHVGSGZTal9jWlptdTdtOWx1STlfM1F6=
YUFfUVlEcXgxMFlQSnVPOW5UanBiRm9IUnZXWm00dXJWOHU5bm52NXZsd0l3dHZTa0M5V1N3RmV=
nOTJSVi1DRlZYa3lkWVBRVjlVcWg4QmMyZ3RSTWpFekY1YU1HOCZzbWlkPXVybC1zaGFyZQ/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3d4b8f18" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a New York Times story</a> about p=
lugging offshore oil wells:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ever since the first offshore platforms went u=
p off Louisiana 85 years ago, the Gulf of Mexico has been an oil and gas ju=
ggernaut. But decades of drilling has left behind more than 14,000 old, unp=
lugged wells at risk of springing dangerous leaks and spills that may cost =
more than $30 billion to plug, a new study has found. Nonproducing wells th=
at haven=E2=80=99t been plugged now outnumber active wells in the gulf, the=
 study says.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The researchers also found that, in federal wa=
ters, nearly 90 percent of the old wells were owned at some point in the pa=
st by giant oil companies known as the =E2=80=9Csupermajors,=E2=80=9D inclu=
ding BP, Shell, Chevron and Exxon. Under federal law, that means those comp=
anies would still be responsible for cleanup costs, even though they might =
have sold the wells in the past, the study=E2=80=99s authors said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oil and gas companies are responsible under fe=
deral and state rules for securely plugging wells that are no longer in ser=
vice. In the boom-and-bust world of oil and gas drilling, though, operators=
 frequently go bankrupt, leaving wells orphaned and unplugged, and taxpayer=
s on the hook. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, in federal waters, the government can h=
old prior owners of wells liable for plugging them, even if the current own=
ers go under or otherwise don=E2=80=99t fulfill their cleanup obligations. =
Eighty-seven percent of wells under federal jurisdiction were once owned by=
 one of the supermajors, many of which have recently booked record profits.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSo for federal waters, these companie=
s with deep pockets would be on the hook,=E2=80=9D Dr. Agerton said. =E2=80=
=9CThere=E2=80=99s someone to go after.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But maybe not forever?</p>
